1.4 Processors Read and Interpret Instructions Stored in Memory
    1.4.0 How to use shell to run the executable
    1.4.1 Hardware organization of a system
        Buses: electronic conduits carrying bites between other components. Transferred fixed-size bytes: words. 
        I/O devices: keyboard, mouse, display, disk drive
        Main memory: dynamic random access memory (DRAM)
        Processor: CPU (core: program counter). Processor reads the instruction pointed by the PC, execute it, then PC moves to the next instruction. Simple operations: load, store, operate, jump

    1.4.2 Running the hello program
        type the command into shell,  codes travel from disk to memory
        process executes the instructions. String copied from memory to register, then to display.


